etymologies: mid 16th century (in an earlier sense). From post-classical Latin titularius, noun and adjective from classical Latin titulus + -ārius

definitions: Of or relating to a title or name; of the nature of or constituting a title; = "titular".
That exists or is such only in title or name; holding or bearing a title without exercising the functions implied by it; nominal.
From whom or which a title or name is taken; = "titular".
A person who holds a title to an office, benefice, or possession, irrespective of the functions, duties, or rights attaching to it.
The set of titles borne by a monarch or ruler.

notes.text: Chiefly used with reference to monarchs of the ancient Near East, e.g. the pharaohs of Egypt.
